<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-roots-of-quadratic-and-cubic-equations" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Roots of Quadratic and Cubic Equations</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.6 Graphical Methods
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Solve quadratic and cubic equations graphically
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on structured lesson plan-->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        15 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To discover that the roots of an equation are the points where its graph intersects the x-axis.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                    <p>
                        Provide graph paper or graphing software. Guide learners to observe the relationship between the equation <m>y = f(x)</m> and the solutions to <m>f(x) = 0</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                Imagine you are a mathematical detective tasked with finding the "hidden" solutions to equations. Your most powerful tool is the graph.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>What to do</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Solve the equation <m>x^2 - 4 = 0</m>. What values of <m>x</m> make this true?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Look at the graph of <m>y = x^2 - 4</m> below.
                        </p>
                        <image width="65%">
                            <latex-image label="Graph_activity-quadratic-detective">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[
                                    axis lines=center,
                                    axis equal image,
                                    xlabel={$x$}, ylabel={$y$},
                                    xmin=-3, xmax=3, ymin=-5, ymax=3,
                                    tick style={black},
                                    grid=both,
                                    major grid style={gray!80},
                                    minor grid style={gray!20},
                                    minor tick num=4
                                ]
                                    \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-2.5:2.5, samples=60] {x^2 - 4};
                                    \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2pt, color=black] coordinates {(0,-4)};
                                    \node[below right] at (axis cs:0,-4) {$(0,-4)$};
                                    \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2pt, color=red] coordinates {(-2,0) (2,0)};
                                    \node[above right] at (axis cs:-2,0) {?};
                                    \node[above left] at (axis cs:2,0) {?};
                                \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                        <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><p>At what coordinates do the red "clue markers" sit?</p></li>
                            <li><p>What is the value of <m>y</m> at these points?</p></li>
                            <li><p>How do the <m>x</m>-coordinates of these points compare to your algebraic solutions from Step 1?</p></li>
                        </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                             Based on your investigation, if you wanted to find the roots of a complex cubic equation like <m>x^3 - x^2 - 2x = 0</m>, how could you use a graph of <m>y = x^3 - x^2 - 2x</m> to find them without doing any hard algebra?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Use the following graph of <m>y = x^3 - x^2 - 2x</m> to find the solutions to <m>x^3 - x^2 - 2x = 0</m>. 
                        <image width="65%">
                            <latex-image label="Graph_activity-cubic">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[
                                    axis lines=center,
                                    axis equal image,
                                    xlabel={$x$}, ylabel={$y$},
                                    xmin=-3, xmax=3, ymin=-3, ymax=3,
                                    tick style={black},
                                    grid=both,
                                    major grid style={gray!80},
                                    minor grid style={gray!20},
                                    minor tick num=4
                                ]
                                    \addplot[red, thick, &lt;-&gt;, domain=-1.5:2.3, samples=60] {x^3 - x^2 - 2*x};
                                \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                        </p>
                        <solution>
                            <p>
                            <image width="65%">
                                <latex-image label="Graph_activity-cubic-solution">
                                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[
                                        axis lines=center,
                                        axis equal image,
                                        xlabel={$x$}, ylabel={$y$},
                                        xmin=-3, xmax=3, ymin=-3, ymax=3,
                                        tick style={black},
                                        grid=both,
                                        major grid style={gray!80},
                                        minor grid style={gray!20},
                                        minor tick num=4
                                    ]
                                        \addplot[red, thick, &lt;-&gt;, domain=-1.5:2.3, samples=60] {x^3 - x^2 - 2*x};
                                        \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=1pt, color=blue] coordinates {(-1,0) (0,0) (2,0)};
                                        \node[above left] at (axis cs:-1,0) {$x=-1$};
                                        \node[above right] at (axis cs:0,0) {$x=0$};
                                        \node[below right] at (axis cs:2,0) {$x=2$};
                                    \end{axis}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                            The graph intersects the <m>x</m>-axis at three points: <m>x=-1</m>, <m>x=0</m>, and <m>x=2</m>. These are the roots of the equation <m>x^3 - x^2 - 2x = 0</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the concept of graphical roots for quadratic and cubic equations.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Link the x-intercepts found in the activity to the solutions of the equation <m>f(x) = 0</m>. Explain that "roots" and "zeros" are other names for these solutions.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Visualization:</alert> Emphasize that a quadratic graph (parabola) can have 0, 1, or 2 roots, while a cubic graph can have 1, 2, or 3 roots.
                    </p>
                </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Challenges:</alert> Discuss the limitations of graphical methods, such as:
                            <ul>
                                <li><p><term>Accuracy:</term> Reading values from a grid is often an approximation.</p></li>
                                <li><p><term>Scale:</term> Missing roots that fall outside the plotted range.</p></li>
                                <li><p><term>Tangency:</term> Difficulty in identifying exact repeated roots where the graph just touches the axis.</p></li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            The <term>roots</term> (or solutions) of an equation <m>f(x) = 0</m> are the <m>x</m>-coordinates of the points where the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m> intersects the <m>x</m>-axis.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Quadratic Equations:</alert> The roots of a quadratic equation are the x-coordinates where the graph intersects the x-axis.
             For example, the graph of <m>y = x^2 + 5x + 6</m> intersects the x-axis at <m>x = -3</m> and <m>x = -2</m>.
             These points are the roots of the equation.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Cubic Equations:</alert> The roots of a cubic equation are the x-coordinates where the graph intersects the x-axis.
                For example, the graph of <m>y = x^3 - 6x^2 + 11x - 6</m> intersects the x-axis at <m>x=1, x=2,</m> and <m>x=3</m>.
                 These points are the roots of the equation.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Solving Quadratic Equations Graphically</alert>
            <ol>
                <li><p>Rearrange the equation into the form <m>ax^2 + bx + c = 0</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>Plot the function <m>y = ax^2 + bx + c</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>The roots are the <m>x</m>-values where the parabola crosses the <m>x</m>-axis.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <image width="65%">
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    axis lines=center,
                    axis equal image,
                    xlabel={$x$}, ylabel={$y$},
                    xmin=-3, xmax=3, ymin=-3, ymax=3,
                    tick style={black},
                    grid=both,
                    major grid style={gray!80},
                    minor grid style={gray!20},
                    minor tick num=4
                ]
                    \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-2.2:2.2, samples=60] {x^2 - 2};
                    \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2pt, color=red] coordinates {(1.414,0) (-1.414,0)};
                    \node[above right] at (axis cs:1.414,0) {Root};
                    \node[above left] at (axis cs:-1.414,0) {Root};
                \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>

        <p>
            <alert>Solving Cubic Equations Graphically</alert>
            <ol>
                <li><p>Rearrange the equation into the form <m>ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d = 0</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>Plot the function <m>y = ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>The roots are the <m>x</m>-values where the curve crosses the <m>x</m>-axis. A cubic can have 1, 2, or 3 real roots.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <image width="65%">
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    axis lines=center,
                    axis equal image,
                    xlabel={$x$}, ylabel={$y$},
                    xmin=-2.5, xmax=2.5, ymin=-3, ymax=3,
                    tick style={black},
                    grid=both,
                    major grid style={gray!80},
                    minor grid style={gray!20},
                    minor tick num=4
                ]
                    \addplot[red, thick, &lt;-&gt;, domain=-2.1:2.1, samples=60] {0.5*x^3 - 2*x};
                    \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2pt, color=blue] coordinates {(2,0) (0,0) (-2,0)};
                    \node at (axis cs:1,1) {3 Roots};
                \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>
    </insight>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Solve the equation <m>x^2 - 2x - 3 = 0</m> graphically.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let <m>y = x^2 - 2x - 3</m>. We create a table of values:
            </p>
            <tabular bottom="minor" top="minor" left="minor" right="minor">
                <row>
                    <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-4</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
                Plotting these points gives the following parabola:
            </p>
            <image xml:id="img-roots-quadratic" width="65%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        axis lines=center,
                        axis equal image,
                        xlabel={$x$}, ylabel={$y$},
                        xmin=-4, xmax=6, ymin=-6, ymax=6,
                        tick style={black},
                        grid=both,
                        major grid style={gray!80},
                        minor grid style={gray!20},
                        minor tick num=1
                    ]
                        \addplot[blue, thick, &lt;-&gt;, domain=-2.1:4.1, samples=60] {x^2 - 2*x - 3};
                        \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2pt, color=black] coordinates {(-1,0) (3,0)};
                        \node[above left, fill=white, opacity=0.7] at (axis cs:-1,0) {$x=-1$};
                        \node[above left, fill=white, opacity=0.7] at (axis cs:3,0) {$x=3$};
                    \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p>
                The graph intersects the <m>x</m>-axis at <m>x = -1</m> and <m>x = 3</m>.
                Therefore, the roots of <m>x^2 - 2x - 3 = 0</m> are <m>x = -1</m> and <m>x = 3</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                From the following graph of <m>x^3 - 3x + 1 = 0</m>, estimate the roots of the equation.
            </p>
            <image xml:id="img-roots-cubic" width="65%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        axis lines=center,
                        axis equal image,
                        xlabel={$x$}, ylabel={$y$},
                        xmin=-4, xmax=4, ymin=-6, ymax=6,
                        tick style={black},
                        grid=both,
                        major grid style={gray!80},
                        minor grid style={gray!20},
                        minor tick num=4
                    ]
                    \addplot[blue, thick, &lt;-&gt;, domain=-2.3:2.05, samples=60] {x^3 - 3*x + 1};
                    \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                From the graph, the curve crosses the <m>x</m>-axis at three points. Approximating from the grid:
                <ul>
                    <li><p><m>x = -1.85</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>x = 0.38</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>x = 1.5</m></p></li>
                </ul>
                These are the roots of the equation <m>x^3 - 3x + 1 = 0</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the roots of <m>x^2 - 4x + 4 = 0</m> graphically.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Plotting <m>y = x^2 - 4x + 4</m>:
            </p>
            <image xml:id="img-roots-repeated" width="65%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \begin{axis}[
                        axis lines=center,
                        axis equal image,
                        xlabel={$x$}, ylabel={$y$},
                        xmin=-1, xmax=5, ymin=-1, ymax=5,
                        tick style={black},
                        grid=both,
                        major grid style={gray!80},
                        minor grid style={gray!20},
                        minor tick num=4
                    ]
                        \addplot[blue, thick, domain=0:4, samples=60] {x^2 - 4*x + 4};
                        \addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=2pt, color=black] coordinates {(2,0)};
                        \node[below right] at (axis cs:2,0) {$x=2$};
                    \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p>
                The graph touches the <m>x</m>-axis at only one point, <m>(2, 0)</m>.
                This means the equation <m>x^2 - 4x + 4 = 0</m> has one repeated root, <m>x = 2</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The graph of <m>y = x^2 + k</m> is shown below. If the graph does not cross the <m>x</m>-axis, what can you say about the roots of the equation <m>x^2 + k = 0</m>?
                </p>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            axis lines=center,
                            axis equal image,
                            xlabel={$x$}, ylabel={$y$},
                            xmin=-2, xmax=2, ymin=-1, ymax=4,
                            tick style={black},
                            grid=both,
                            major grid style={gray!80},
                            minor grid style={gray!20},
                            minor tick num=4
                        ]
                            \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-1.5:1.5, samples=60] {x^2 + 1};
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    If the graph does not intersect the <m>x</m>-axis, the equation has no real roots.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Solve the equation <m>x^3 - x^2 - 2x = 0</m> by plotting the graph of <m>y = x^3 - x^2 - 2x</m> for <m>-2 \le x \le 3</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Factoring <m>y = x(x^2 - x - 2) = x(x - 2)(x + 1)</m>.
                </p>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image label="Graph_exercise-cubic-roots">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            axis lines=center,
                            axis equal image,
                            xlabel={$x$}, ylabel={$y$},
                            xmin=-2.5, xmax=3.5, ymin=-3, ymax=4,
                            tick style={black},
                            grid=both,
                            major grid style={gray!80},
                            minor grid style={gray!20},
                            minor tick num=4
                        ]
                            \addplot[red, thick, domain=-2:3, samples=60] {x^3 - x^2 - 2*x};
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                <p>
                    The graph crosses the <m>x</m>-axis at <m>x = -1, x = 0,</m> and <m>x = 2</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Use a graph to estimate the roots of <m>x^2 - 5 = 0</m>. (Hint: Plot <m>y = x^2 - 5</m>).
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image label="Graph_exercise-quadratic-roots">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            axis lines=center,
                            axis equal image,
                            xlabel={$x$}, ylabel={$y$},
                            xmin=-3, xmax=3, ymin=-6, ymax=5,
                            tick style={black},
                            grid=both,
                            major grid style={gray!80},
                            minor grid style={gray!20},
                            minor tick num=4
                        ]
                            \addplot[blue, thick, domain=-2.5:2.5, samples=60] {x^2 - 5};
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                <p>
                    The roots are <m>x = \pm \sqrt{5}</m>. Graphically, these are approximately <m>x \approx -2.2</m> and <m>x \approx 2.2</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Here is the graph of the function <m>y = x^3 - 6x^2 + 11x - 6</m>.
                </p>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image label="Graph_exercise-cubic-roots-2">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[
                                axis lines=center,
                                axis equal image,
                                xlabel={$x$}, ylabel={$y$},
                                tick style={black},
                                grid=both,
                                xmin=-0.5, xmax=4, ymin=-3, ymax=3,
                                major grid style={gray!80},
                                minor grid style={gray!20},
                                minor tick num=4
                            ]
                                \addplot[red, thick, &lt;-&gt;, domain=0.4:3.5, samples=60] {x^3 - 6*x^2 + 11*x - 6};
                            \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the roots of <m>x</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Use this graph to find the solution of the equation <md>x^3 - 6x^2 + 11x - 6 = 1</md>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                From the graph, we can see that the roots are approximately <m>x = 1</m>, <m>x = 2</m>, and <m>x = 3</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                To solve <m>x^3 - 6x^2 + 11x - 6 = 1</m>, we can rearrange it to <m>x^3 - 6x^2 + 11x - 7 = 0</m>.
                                This means we need to find where the graph of <m>y = x^3 - 6x^2 + 11x - 7</m> intersects the x-axis.
                                Drawing the horizontal line <m>y = 1</m> on the graph, we can see that it intersects the curve at approximately <m>x = 1.5</m>.
                            </p>
                            <image width="65%">
                            <latex-image label="Graph_exercise-cubic-roots-2-soln">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[
                                    axis lines=center,
                                    axis equal image,
                                    xlabel={$x$}, ylabel={$y$},
                                    tick style={black},
                                    grid=both,
                                    xmin=-0.5, xmax=4, ymin=-3, ymax=3,
                                    major grid style={gray!80},
                                    minor grid style={gray!20},
                                    minor tick num=4
                                ]
                                    \addplot[red, thick, &lt;-&gt;, domain=0.4:3.5, samples=60] {x^3 - 6*x^2 + 11*x - 6};
                                    \addplot[blue, thick, &lt;-&gt;, domain=-0.5:4, samples=60] {1};
                                \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>

            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find the solutions of the equation <m>x^3 - 2x^2 + x - 1 = 0</m> graphically.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <image width="65%">
                    <latex-image label="Graph_exercise-cubic-roots-3">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            axis lines=center,
                            axis equal image,
                            xlabel={$x$}, ylabel={$y$},
                            xmin=-2, xmax=4, ymin=-3, ymax=4,
                            tick style={black},
                            grid=both,
                            major grid style={gray!80},
                            minor grid style={gray!20},
                            minor tick num=4
                        ]
                            \addplot[red, thick, domain=-1:3.5, samples=60] {x^3 - 2*x^2 + x - 1};
                        \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
                <p>
                    Plotting <m>y = x^3 - 2x^2 + x - 1</m> shows that it crosses the <m>x</m>-axis at approximately <m>x = 1.5</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Focus on quadratic equations first. Use technology (like Desmos) to visualize how shifting a graph vertically changes the number of roots.
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Practice plotting both quadratic and cubic functions accurately to read roots from the graph.
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        Explore the relationship between the coefficients of a cubic equation and the number of real roots. Investigate "turning points" and how they relate to the existence of roots.
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>

